00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:10.970
- All right, so if you
look at the written

00:02:10.970 --> 00:02:13.850
record of human thought,
it's pretty clear

00:02:13.850 --> 00:02:21.360
that for at least 500 years
and arguably for 2,500 years,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.140
humans have wondered whether
there were other worlds that

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:27.620
were inhabited and whether
or not we could somehow

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:30.290
come into contact with those
worlds and explore them.

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:35.060
And what I want
to begin by saying

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:38.750
is that this is a very special
moment in human history

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:43.580
where we're going to do
something very special, which

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:45.470
is that we have
for the first time

00:02:45.470 --> 00:02:49.190
the technological ability
to actually go and answer

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:50.190
that question.

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:52.820
And so there's a great
deal of excitement

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:58.460
worldwide amongst astronomers
and astrobiologists

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:00.290
that really within
the next 10 years

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:03.260
we might detect the
presence of life

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:05.240
on planets orbiting other stars.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:10.040
And so we're going to talk about
these exoplanets here today.

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:13.820
We have two of the
world's experts

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:17.990
and leading thinkers on
this really great question.

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:22.850
Our second speaker is going to
be Professor Lisa Kaltenegger,

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:26.890
who is the director of the
Carl Sagan Institute at Cornell

00:03:26.890 --> 00:03:29.480
where she is also
professor of astronomy.

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:34.340
And there are few souls,
on this planet at least,

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:38.720
who have thought more
deeply and for longer

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:43.250
than what it would really take
to infer the presence of life

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:45.410
through telescopic observations.

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:47.690
So among many of the
exciting questions

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:51.680
that Lisa has investigated
are what would the earth look

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:54.350
like to an alien astronomer?

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:56.090
And how did the
Earth's appearance

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:59.570
change to that alien astronomer
as a function of time?

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:03.680
The Earth has not always
appeared as it now does.

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:08.360
Could we detect the presence
of geological activity

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:12.500
like volcanoes if you were
a remote astronomer gazing

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:14.570
across the vastness of space?

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:17.420
And which stars we
should begin by looking

00:04:17.420 --> 00:04:20.240
at as we go and do
this exploration

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:23.520
with our telescopes.

00:04:23.520 --> 00:04:27.980
Our first speaker, though,
will be Laura Kreidberg.

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:33.030
And Dr. Kreidberg is a junior
fellow in the Harvard Society

00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:34.160
of Fellows.

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:36.920
And maybe to set up a
bit of a juxtaposition

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:41.120
for the purpose of this talk,
whereas Lisa is the theorist,

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:45.410
Laura is the observer.

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:49.040
And Dr. Kreidberg is
really a world leader

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:54.960
in using novel techniques
and pushing observatories

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:58.890
to achieve unprecedented
