00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:24.340
- All right, thank
you, everybody.

00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:27.640
It's my pleasure to be here.

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:31.120
And I have the honor of speaking
about a topic that really ties

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:34.670
together all of the themes
of today, which are life,

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:38.290
the earth, and space, which
is the question of is there

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:39.780
life elsewhere?

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.040
And as Dave said, humans
have been thinking

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:43.660
about this for a long time.

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:47.150
I would guess before
recorded history,

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:50.980
humans have been
thinking about this.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:52.450
But the place I'd
like to start is

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:56.110
in the early 1960s when
an astronomer named

00:05:56.110 --> 00:06:00.430
Frank Drake developed the
first scientific framework

00:06:00.430 --> 00:06:03.070
for talking about the
possibility of detecting

00:06:03.070 --> 00:06:06.070
inhabited planets in the galaxy.

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:08.942
And so he wrote down
this famous equation.

00:06:08.942 --> 00:06:10.150
It looks like it's not there.

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:12.483
Well, I'm not allowed to have
equations in talks anyway,

00:06:12.483 --> 00:06:13.990
so that's fine.

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:16.870
So the way Frank Drake
thought about this

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:18.620
was he started by
saying, OK, well,

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:21.220
how many stars
are in the galaxy?

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:23.260
Presumably you need
the star as a source

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:25.430
of energy for your life.

00:06:25.430 --> 00:06:28.400
And then he said,
how many of those

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:31.340
stars host planets, in
particular planets that

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:32.930
are likely to be habitable?

00:06:32.930 --> 00:06:35.390
We'll come back to that later.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:38.080
And finally, how often
does life actually

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:40.900
arise on those potentially
habitable planets?

00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:43.870
And if it does arise,
can we detect it?

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:46.380
And so the goal was
to get a number--

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:49.780
number of potentially
detectable inhabited planets

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:51.040
in the galaxy.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:52.480
And this all sounds fine.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:54.740
It's a very organized
way of thinking about it.

00:06:54.740 --> 00:06:57.340
The problem was that
in 1961, nobody knew

00:06:57.340 --> 00:06:58.970
what any of these terms were.

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:04.380
And the way it was
approached was the way

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:06.840
we were all taught as
young scientists, which

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:09.270
is to develop a
hypothesis and then try

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:10.860
to figure out an
experiment you could

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:13.000
use to test that hypothesis.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.210
And so if your
hypothesis is that there

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:18.630
are other stars in the
galaxy that host planets like

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:21.570
the earth, then your
experiment is can you detect

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:23.235
these Earth-like planets?

00:07:23.235 --> 00:07:24.860
And so folks went
through this exercise

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:29.270
of trying to figure out how
we would go about doing that.

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:32.120
And so the most natural
first question is to say,

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:35.184
can we just take a
picture of the planet,

00:07:35.184 --> 00:07:36.850
maybe block out the
light from the star?

00:07:36.850 --> 00:07:38.950
And it turns out that
this is very, very hard,

00:07:38.950 --> 00:07:43.180
that the earth is 10 billion
times fainter than the sun.

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:44.920
And not only is it
much, much fainter,

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:46.240
it's also very close to it.

00:07:46.240 --> 00:07:48.040
And so the analogy
is that this is

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:51.790
very similar to trying to detect
a firefly next to a lighthouse

00:07:51.790 --> 00:07:53.890
at a distance of a
couple of hundred miles.

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.090
And so this was ruled
out as impossible.

00:07:57.090 --> 00:07:58.640
OK, good.

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:01.530
So another idea was
to try to search

00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:03.540
for a transit of the planet.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:06.180
This is when you get
lucky with your geometry

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:10.710
and the planet goes directly
in front of its parent star.

00:08:10.710 --> 00:08:12.910
And when it does
that, it blocks,

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:16.230
as Alyssa said, a tiny
fraction of the stellar light.

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:18.540
The challenge is that
for an earth-sized planet

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:23.520
around a sun-like star,
it's only one part in 10,000

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:26.520
of the stellar brightness
that gets blocked.

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:28.980
And that was considered also
too difficult to detect.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:33.409
Not only is it difficult to
detect, it's fairly improbable.

00:08:33.409 --> 00:08:35.130
Only half a percent
of the time would

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:38.220
you expect this chance alignment
to work out in your favor.

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:40.450
And it only happens once a year.

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:42.590
And so even if you
did somehow build

00:08:42.590 --> 00:08:46.410
a detector that could see it,
suppose next year you went back

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:48.780
to try to detect
it again and you're

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:50.970
observing from the
ground, could be cloudy.

00:08:50.970 --> 00:08:51.870
It could be daytime.

00:08:51.870 --> 00:08:55.200
You might not be able
to see it at all.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.040
Folks also thought about
trying to detect the influence

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:00.430
of the planet on the stars.

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:02.220
So planets have some mass.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.340
And we normally think of
the star as fixed in space,

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:07.630
but the planet is
orbiting around.

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.830
But really the planet's gravity
tugs on the star a little bit,

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:12.780
and it makes it wobble.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.540
And so you could
imagine that maybe you

00:09:15.540 --> 00:09:18.960
could detect that wobble
by observing the spectrum

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:20.440
of the star, the color.

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:22.500
And when the star is
moving towards you,

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:25.130
its light is a little
bit blueshifted just

00:09:25.130 --> 00:09:26.880
by the Doppler effect,
the same thing that

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.830
makes a siren sound
higher pitched

00:09:28.830 --> 00:09:32.730
as it's coming towards you and
lower pitched as it moves away.

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:35.150
And then as the
planet moves away--

00:09:35.150 --> 00:09:36.900
as the star moves away
from you, its light

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.610
would be then redshifted.

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:42.160
The problem here
is that the size

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:44.470
of the signal, the
amount of motion induced

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:47.560
by the earth on the sun
is only 10 centimeters

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:51.310
a second, which was far too
difficult for any detector

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:54.440
at the time to ever see.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:57.380
And so even though this is
such an exciting question,

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:01.340
everyone was saying, oh, there's
no way, this is too hard,

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:04.110
except for a handful of very
persistent, very stubborn

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:04.610
people.

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:06.530
One of these was Paul Butler.

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:10.280
And he described what it
was like to try to search

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:12.920
for extrasolar planets in 1986.

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:15.080
And what he said
was, "When asked

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:18.020
by other astronomers,
what are you working on,

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:20.210
one could not
respond, I'm searching

00:10:20.210 --> 00:10:21.770
for extrasolar planets.

00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:24.020
Depending on the person,
they might laugh in your face

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.600
or slowly move away from
you like you were pitching

00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:29.540
an alien conspiracy theory."

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:31.760
But nevertheless, they tried.

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:33.230
They kept going.

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:36.650
And this is an amazing,
amazing figure.

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:41.170
This is the discovery data
for an extrasolar planet

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:43.790
that was completely unlike
anything that was ever

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:46.050
seen in the solar system.

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:50.030
So this was from a team of
astronomers who were using

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:51.950
the Doppler wobble technique.

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:56.210
And they measured the velocity
of a star called 51 Pegasi.

00:10:56.210 --> 00:10:57.740
And this is what they saw.

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:59.900
They saw these
characteristic wiggles

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:01.520
that are exactly
what you would expect

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:04.700
if you have a planet tugging
your star back and forth.

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:06.890
The crazy thing about
this is that the amplitude

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:11.270
of that signal was 100
meters per second compared

00:11:11.270 --> 00:11:14.600
to 10 centimeters a second
for what you would expect

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:16.510
for an earth-like planet.

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:18.740
And so I love this quote
from a colleague of mine,

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:21.620
Emily Levesque, where she
said, "The real exciting sound

00:11:21.620 --> 00:11:27.320
in science is not Eureka,
it's huh, that's weird."

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:31.660
And that is exactly
what we're seeing here.

00:11:31.660 --> 00:11:34.730
So the inference
here is that in order

00:11:34.730 --> 00:11:36.380
to have a signal
that large, you have

00:11:36.380 --> 00:11:39.800
to have a planet comparable
in size to Jupiter

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:43.850
orbiting its parent star
in about three days.

00:11:43.850 --> 00:11:45.980
And this was considered
absolutely crazy.

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:47.720
There's no way a planet
could form there.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:49.820
We think that the
material that goes

00:11:49.820 --> 00:11:51.302
into forming
Jupiter-like planets

00:11:51.302 --> 00:11:53.510
would all be vaporized at
temperatures as high as you

00:11:53.510 --> 00:11:55.340
would get so close to the star.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:57.997
And yet here it was.

00:11:57.997 --> 00:11:59.580
And even still, there
were detractors.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:02.255
People thought this was
so nuts that maybe it

00:12:02.255 --> 00:12:04.380
was something on the star,
maybe it was star spots,

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:09.110
maybe it was just something else
until about five years later

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:12.020
when Dave, who we're
fortunate to have here today,

00:12:12.020 --> 00:12:15.410
decided nah, we have to prove
this for real, and went out

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:17.700
and searched for
transits of the planets.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:21.170
And so I'm glad that Alyssa
was amenable to letting him go

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:23.220
do this as a graduate student.

00:12:23.220 --> 00:12:23.720
Yeah.

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:24.470
Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:24.970
Yeah.

00:12:24.970 --> 00:12:28.580
So this was viewed
with some skepticism.

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.680
Is that right, Dave?

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:32.355
- There's a whole back story.

00:12:32.355 --> 00:12:34.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:36.990
But I do like that plot.

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:42.500
- And so this was the
absolute unmistakable proof

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:46.130
that these signals have
to be caused by a planet.

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:51.680
So this was a star that had a
detected radio velocity signal.

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:52.850
The star was wobbling.

00:12:52.850 --> 00:12:55.530
And then Dave went out
and looked exactly when

00:12:55.530 --> 00:12:58.310
he expected the planet to
transit in front of its host

00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:05.140
star and saw this characteristic
dimming of about a percent.

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:07.300
And so this was the
push that everybody

00:13:07.300 --> 00:13:09.280
needed to say, oh,
maybe there actually

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:11.380
are planets around other stars.

00:13:11.380 --> 00:13:13.420
And they might not have
to be like the planets

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:14.860
in this solar system.

00:13:14.860 --> 00:13:17.390
And so the floodgates opened.

00:13:17.390 --> 00:13:19.870
And there are now
over a dozen searches

00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:23.050
using both the transit
technique and the stellar wobble

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:27.670
technique that have been going
on for over two decades now.

00:13:27.670 --> 00:13:31.750
And so I'll fast forward to what
our picture of exoplanets looks

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:34.650
like today.

00:13:34.650 --> 00:13:35.800
And this is what we found.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:38.230
This is the plot showing
the pace of discovery.

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:40.140
This is the number
of known planets,

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:42.150
number of discovered
planets detected every year

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:44.400
between 1995 and today.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.740
There are almost 4,000 of them.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:50.550
We know now that the average
star hosts at least one planet

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:51.090
typically.

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:53.200
Some have many more.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:55.500
And the diversity of
planets is much greater

00:13:55.500 --> 00:13:57.880
than we ever could have
imagined from the solar system.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:14:00.730
So not only did we see these
hot Jupiter-like planets,

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:02.790
the very first ones
that were discovered,

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:06.540
we also see many planets
that are intermediate in size

00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:07.980
between the Earth and Neptune.

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:11.550
We have no solar system
analog for those planets.

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:14.790
We see many, many, many
planets on orbits interior

00:14:14.790 --> 00:14:18.370
to that of Mercury, which is
the closest planet to the sun.

00:14:18.370 --> 00:14:20.310
We see planets
orbiting stars that

00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:23.040
are very different from the
sun, stars that are larger,

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:25.900
stars that are
smaller and cooler.

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:29.240
And as the excitement
about this grew,

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:31.420
so did our technological
capabilities.

00:14:31.420 --> 00:14:33.730
And so that original
question of are there other

00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:36.820
Earth-like planets
suddenly became something

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:38.500
that was within our reach.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:43.960
And what we now know is that
roughly 10% to 20% of stars

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:47.530
host an Earth-size
planet with temperatures

00:14:47.530 --> 00:14:50.680
appropriate for liquid
water on the surface, which

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:54.310
is the canonical
definition for the places

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.040
we're most excited
to try to find life.

00:14:58.990 --> 00:14:59.956
And so here we are.

00:14:59.956 --> 00:15:01.330
We're at this sort
of crossroads.

00:15:01.330 --> 00:15:02.810
Going back to the
Drake equation,

00:15:02.810 --> 00:15:05.110
we now know what a
bunch of the terms are.

00:15:05.110 --> 00:15:09.070
We know that there's about 300
billion stars in the galaxy,

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:12.310
that almost all of those stars
host at least one planet,

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:14.050
and that very,
very many of those

00:15:14.050 --> 00:15:17.680
planets are
potentially habitable.

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:21.250
And so the question
for me is what do we

00:15:21.250 --> 00:15:23.560
do about these last two pieces?

00:15:23.560 --> 00:15:25.870
How often does life develop?

00:15:25.870 --> 00:15:29.180
How can we go about
detecting that life?

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:31.180
And there are a couple
of ways to go about this.

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:33.550
We're going to hear later
in the afternoon from Jill

00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:35.385
about technosignatures.

00:15:35.385 --> 00:15:36.760
I'm going to talk
about something

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:41.260
a little bit different, which
is searching for biosignatures

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:45.410
in the atmospheres
of these planets.

00:15:45.410 --> 00:15:47.880
And this is a little
bit of a gamble.

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:51.410
So I really liked what Stuart
talked about this morning

00:15:51.410 --> 00:15:56.330
about searching for a
black cat in a dark room.

00:15:56.330 --> 00:15:59.660
That definitely feels like what
I do in my day-to-day work.

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:01.120
But it's not exactly--

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:02.990
it's not a bumbling search.

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:05.450
We make these guesses
to say, oh you know,

00:16:05.450 --> 00:16:07.730
maybe the cat is sitting
on top of the dryer

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:09.380
because it's warm up there.

00:16:09.380 --> 00:16:12.090
That's where we would
expect a cat to normally be.

00:16:12.090 --> 00:16:15.440
And so when I think about that
undiscovered in science, to me

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:18.800
it feels a lot like a
sort of calculated gamble.

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:19.660
I grew up in Nevada.

00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:21.170
I know about gambling.

00:16:21.170 --> 00:16:25.430
And so the gamble
that I'm taking

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:31.047
is to study some earth-sized
planets in the habitable zones

00:16:31.047 --> 00:16:31.880
of their host stars.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:36.290
But these planets are very,
very different from the sun.

00:16:36.290 --> 00:16:38.990
And that's because they're
orbiting much smaller stars

00:16:38.990 --> 00:16:41.154
that are a lot cooler.

00:16:41.154 --> 00:16:43.070
And there's a lot of
advantages to doing this.

00:16:43.070 --> 00:16:46.490
We know that small
stars are actually

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:49.220
much more common than
sun-like stars in the galaxy.

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:52.430
So this figure shows
the sun would be one

00:16:52.430 --> 00:16:54.380
of these bright yellow circles.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:57.950
These are all of the stars
within about 10 parsecs,

00:16:57.950 --> 00:17:00.420
so very nearby to the sun.

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:04.079
And you can see that most of
them are quite a bit smaller.

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:06.420
Not only are small
stars more common,

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:08.970
the habitable zone
is also closer in.

00:17:08.970 --> 00:17:11.160
So if you're searching
for transiting planets,

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:14.280
the transits are more frequent,
the transit probability

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:17.970
is higher, and most importantly
the planet is much larger

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:19.130
relative to the star.

00:17:19.130 --> 00:17:23.960
And so they're easier
to characterize.

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:27.859
And excitingly, we've started to
detect a lot of these planets.

00:17:27.859 --> 00:17:30.110
It's so exciting that it
made the Google Doodle, which

00:17:30.110 --> 00:17:31.651
I think is a sign
that you've made it

00:17:31.651 --> 00:17:38.120
as a scientist when your results
end up on the Google homepage.

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:41.700
So I really identify with
the moon in this animation.

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:45.110
So yeah, we now know
of about a dozen

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:48.680
nearby terrestrial planets
orbiting these very small stars

00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:50.930
where we have some hope of
studying their atmospheres

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:52.263
and searching for signs of life.

00:17:54.870 --> 00:17:57.560
However, there are some
caveats that I should mention.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:17:59.450
And this is why
this is risky, which

00:17:59.450 --> 00:18:03.110
is that small stars are very,
very different from the sun.

00:18:03.110 --> 00:18:05.210
They are bright in
the ultraviolet,

00:18:05.210 --> 00:18:08.150
so they emit a lot of
high-energy radiation

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:11.360
in their young lifetimes that
can be very dangerous to life

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:15.810
trying to develop on the surface
of the planets orbiting them.

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:18.570
It could also evaporate the
atmosphere of the planet.

00:18:18.570 --> 00:18:21.320
So we're not sure whether
planets around these stars

00:18:21.320 --> 00:18:24.770
can even hold on to
atmospheres at all.

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:28.550
They have powerful flares
that could also disrupt

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:30.450
the development of life.

00:18:30.450 --> 00:18:34.550
And finally, the planets are
expected to be tidally locked

00:18:34.550 --> 00:18:35.290
to the stars.

00:18:35.290 --> 00:18:39.180
That is to say they have a hot
day side and a cold night side,

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:43.340
just like the moon is tidally
locked by the Earth's gravity.

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:46.760
And in this situation,
you can imagine

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:50.791
that you're not going to
have a smooth temperature all

00:18:50.791 --> 00:18:52.540
the way around the
surface of your planet.

00:18:52.540 --> 00:18:53.790
You'll have a really hot part.

00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:54.920
You'll have a cold part.

00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:57.230
You might worry about
your atmosphere freezing

00:18:57.230 --> 00:19:00.290
out on the cold side, so you
get a snow cone situation

00:19:00.290 --> 00:19:04.400
where there's ice on one side
and rock on the other side.

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:06.500
And so there are a
lot of detractors

00:19:06.500 --> 00:19:10.270
who argue against
searching for atmospheres,

00:19:10.270 --> 00:19:14.410
searching for signs of
life on planets like this.

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:16.090
But I think that's silly.

00:19:16.090 --> 00:19:18.820
And so this is what I do.

00:19:18.820 --> 00:19:24.010
I'm interested in trying
to measure the compositions

00:19:24.010 --> 00:19:24.920
of the atmospheres.

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:26.860
This is a little
animation showing how

00:19:26.860 --> 00:19:28.910
we would go about doing this.

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:31.870
And the idea is that when the
planet is in front of the star,

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:33.850
a tiny fraction of
the starlight will

00:19:33.850 --> 00:19:36.010
filter through the
planet's atmosphere.

00:19:36.010 --> 00:19:39.490
And it can get
absorbed by molecules

00:19:39.490 --> 00:19:41.140
that are present there.

00:19:41.140 --> 00:19:44.800
And depending on what
the molecules are,

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:48.070
they have different
opacities, different levels

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:50.600
of transparency at
different wavelengths.

00:19:50.600 --> 00:19:54.430
And so if we measure the size of
the planet in different colors,

00:19:54.430 --> 00:19:56.230
we can work backwards
and figure out what

00:19:56.230 --> 00:19:57.700
the atmosphere is made out of.

00:20:00.440 --> 00:20:03.110
And just to illustrate with
a more close-to-home example,

00:20:03.110 --> 00:20:06.250
this is what the Earth
looks like in the infrared.

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:08.500
That's the moon
in the background.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:11.150
And if I move to a
different wavelength

00:20:11.150 --> 00:20:17.070
where ozone is very
opaque, it looks like this.

00:20:17.070 --> 00:20:20.650
You can see these
small differences.

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:23.830
And so that's what we're
looking for in the atmospheres

00:20:23.830 --> 00:20:24.820
of these other planets.

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:28.280
This actually works.

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:30.580
This is my one science
result that I'll show you.

00:20:30.580 --> 00:20:32.530
We don't have yet
the sensitivity

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:35.050
to look at planets
that are this small.

00:20:35.050 --> 00:20:37.810
But this is a planet
similar to Neptune.

00:20:37.810 --> 00:20:39.940
And we detected water
in its atmosphere.

00:20:39.940 --> 00:20:44.440
So those two big bumps are where
the planet radius is larger

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:50.680
because water vapor is absorbing
and blocking the stellar light.

00:20:50.680 --> 00:20:54.280
And so what we
expect is very soon,

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:56.830
not with telescopes that
we have available yet,

00:20:56.830 --> 00:20:58.810
but in the near future
with James Webb, which

00:20:58.810 --> 00:21:01.180
is the successor to the
Hubble Space Telescope,

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:03.250
that we're going to
start to be able to make

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:05.620
these measurements for
Earth-sized planets

00:21:05.620 --> 00:21:07.450
around the smallest stars.

00:21:07.450 --> 00:21:10.270
And so this is a
result from a paper

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:13.990
I wrote with my office
mate, Caroline Morley.

00:21:13.990 --> 00:21:16.510
And we were sitting
around, and we were saying,

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:21.670
OK, we have no idea what the
atmospheres of these planets

00:21:21.670 --> 00:21:22.880
are going to be like.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:25.090
And so to deal with
that uncertainty,

00:21:25.090 --> 00:21:29.690
we said, well, we could use the
solar system as inspiration.

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:31.960
We have different
kinds of atmospheres

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:33.970
for the solar system planets.

00:21:33.970 --> 00:21:36.779
And so here we were
like, well, maybe it

00:21:36.779 --> 00:21:38.320
has an atmosphere
like the earth that

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:41.380
has a lot of water
vapor in it or maybe it

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:43.570
has an atmosphere
more like Venus

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:47.230
that is dominated by
CO2, carbon dioxide,

00:21:47.230 --> 00:21:48.920
or instead it
could have methane,

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:54.030
which is a situation we see on
Titan, one of Saturn's moons.

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:56.230
And so we made a
prediction for what

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:59.230
the signal should look like for
these different atmospheres.

00:21:59.230 --> 00:22:01.330
And we found that
this is something

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:04.600
we will be able to detect
using the James Webb Space

00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:07.430
Telescope with a fairly
reasonable amount of observing

00:22:07.430 --> 00:22:07.930
time.

00:22:07.930 --> 00:22:09.888
And so this is something
we can look forward to

00:22:09.888 --> 00:22:12.790
within the next
five years or so.

00:22:12.790 --> 00:22:14.380
And normally when
I talk about this,

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:16.799
I feel like I have to--
like I'm on the job market

00:22:16.799 --> 00:22:19.090
and I have to have some sort
of punch line where I say,

00:22:19.090 --> 00:22:22.730
oh yes, and this will tell us
that the planet is inhabited

00:22:22.730 --> 00:22:23.230
or not.

00:22:23.230 --> 00:22:25.620
And for the purposes
of this talk,

00:22:25.620 --> 00:22:28.030
I'll be honest and
say we have no idea.

00:22:28.030 --> 00:22:31.570
We have absolutely no
idea what we will find.

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:34.390
But we're trying to design
an experiment in a smart way

00:22:34.390 --> 00:22:37.690
where we can learn at least
the very beginning of what

00:22:37.690 --> 00:22:40.030
kind of chemical inventory
these planets might

00:22:40.030 --> 00:22:43.870
have so we can start assessing
whether they host life or not.

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:50.900
And so to end, I'll leave you
with a quote from Frank Drake.

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:53.300
I had the honor of meeting
him a couple of years ago.

00:22:53.300 --> 00:22:56.330
And the question I had for him
was knowing what we know now,

00:22:56.330 --> 00:22:59.090
what do you think the chances
are of discovering life

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:00.140
elsewhere?

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:02.840
And he said, "100%."

00:23:02.840 --> 00:23:05.960
But I'll add the caveat
to that, that in order

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:09.650
to find that life, we have to
keep an open mind about how

00:23:09.650 --> 00:23:11.910
and where we search.

00:23:11.910 --> 00:23:12.669
Thank you.

00:23:12.669 --> 00:23:16.092
[APPLAUSE]

