00:23:35.850 --> 00:23:39.390
to what we're trying to do,
what we're trying to achieve.

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:42.210
And Dave already mentioned this.

00:23:42.210 --> 00:23:46.620
If you just take a
second to think that we

00:23:46.620 --> 00:23:50.070
are the generation that might.

00:23:50.070 --> 00:23:52.837
We have the technological
possibility,

00:23:52.837 --> 00:23:54.420
but we don't know
how hard it is going

00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:58.470
to be to actually spot life,
if they're unique signatures.

00:23:58.470 --> 00:24:00.450
That's what we're
going to talk about.

00:24:00.450 --> 00:24:05.340
But we are the first generation
in all of human history

00:24:05.340 --> 00:24:10.110
that has the chance to
figure out if we are alone

00:24:10.110 --> 00:24:12.000
in the universe.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.940
It's us.

00:24:13.940 --> 00:24:17.900
I think that is one of the
most amazing times ever.

00:24:17.900 --> 00:24:22.760
And sometimes people pick when
they would like to be born.

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:25.970
And I would pick
now all the time,

00:24:25.970 --> 00:24:28.040
because living in
the time where are

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:32.360
we going to get this connection
to the cosmos, where we're

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:35.090
going to look up at the stars
and not just statistically

00:24:35.090 --> 00:24:40.130
right now say 1,
2, 3, 4, 5, right?

00:24:40.130 --> 00:24:42.680
One out of five
stars has a planet

00:24:42.680 --> 00:24:46.481
small enough and at the right
