And this is, of course, why
we need excellent observers

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:01.760
like Laura and Dave
to make this work

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:04.460
to let us find these features.

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:06.850
This is what one of the
telescopes looks like.

00:40:06.850 --> 00:40:09.730
It's one of the extremely
large telescopes envisioned

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:12.230
to be in Chile.

00:40:12.230 --> 00:40:15.110
It's a 40 meter
telescope on the ground

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:19.580
because you have to take out
the atmospheric disturbance

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:21.440
on the image you
collect from the ground,

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:23.120
so it needs to be bigger.

00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:26.540
And this is the telescope,
the James Webb Space Telescope

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:29.090
we should be launching in 2021.

00:40:29.090 --> 00:40:31.280
And while saying
that, we have just

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:34.630
launched this year an
amazing small telescope,

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:37.280
the test satellite
that is actually

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:41.330
not just giving us statistics,
because I said count to five,

00:40:41.330 --> 00:40:45.200
one out of five stars has a
planet that could be like ours.

00:40:45.200 --> 00:40:49.490
This test satellite that we
just launched in April this year

00:40:49.490 --> 00:40:52.130
actually started taking
science data in July.

00:40:52.130 --> 00:40:55.370
And it's telling you
which of these stars

00:40:55.370 --> 00:40:58.490
actually does have the
planets that could potentially

00:40:58.490 --> 00:41:00.120
be like ours.

00:41:00.120 --> 00:41:04.040
And it's going to give us our
closest travel destination.

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:06.990
Even so, this is going
to be in the far future.

00:41:06.990 --> 00:41:08.570
But in the last
couple of minutes,

00:41:08.570 --> 00:41:11.660
what I wanted to show you
is now this is undiscovered.

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:14.840
And this is out-of-the-box
thinking that we need

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:19.080
to actually find life in
different environments.

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:21.530
We can use Earth
as a Rosetta stone.

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:23.010
But we basically
are not just going

00:41:23.010 --> 00:41:27.080
to use life on earth like
plants and everything you see.

00:41:27.080 --> 00:41:31.880
We use life in the deep oceans
or we use life like water bears

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:33.860
that basically survive
kind of everything.

00:41:33.860 --> 00:41:36.590
They even took them to the
International Space Station,

00:41:36.590 --> 00:41:38.330
put them out, no shelter.

00:41:38.330 --> 00:41:40.610
Three days later, they put
them back in, put water on,

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:43.580
and it was like da, da, da,
da, da, I'm fine, right?

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:47.540
So life is incredibly
diverse and versatile even

00:41:47.540 --> 00:41:48.950
on our own planet.

00:41:48.950 --> 00:41:51.530
And in our search,
we need to put that

00:41:51.530 --> 00:41:53.600
into our search strategy.

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:57.680
We cannot just look for a planet
that's exactly a copy of ours,

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:00.650
because even with billions
of planets in our own solar

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:04.700
system, the chances to find one
that's exactly like ours right

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:09.360
now is probably not as high
as you'd like it to be.

00:42:09.360 --> 00:42:11.400
But if it's just a
little bit different,

00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:14.540
we already know of life
that can survive there.

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:16.790
So if you, for example,
walk through Yellowstone,

00:42:16.790 --> 00:42:19.700
all these beautiful
colors is actually

00:42:19.700 --> 00:42:22.884
biota that lives in
different conditions.

00:42:22.884 --> 00:42:24.550
And this is just a
really funny cartoon.

00:42:24.550 --> 00:42:27.440
It's like, what do you
mean extreme, right?

00:42:27.440 --> 00:42:30.290
Because what's extreme for
us, for other life [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:30.290 --> 00:42:33.480
of the earth, for other
biota is perfectly fine.

00:42:33.480 --> 00:42:34.910
It's where they strive.

00:42:34.910 --> 00:42:38.450
So the analog for what
conditions allow for life

00:42:38.450 --> 00:42:41.720
on the earth are much
bigger than what we usually

00:42:41.720 --> 00:42:45.200
think about, because we don't
think about these extreme forms

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:46.530
of life.

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:50.210
And so one of my PhD students
put together a color catalogue

00:42:50.210 --> 00:42:54.770
of life for going to many, many
different places on the earth,

00:42:54.770 --> 00:42:57.710
taking this biota, and
then saying how would

00:42:57.710 --> 00:43:01.940
it actually look like if you
saw a planet that was dominated,

00:43:01.940 --> 00:43:05.150
let's say by an algae
bloom or by something else?

00:43:05.150 --> 00:43:08.210
And it changes the
color and probably also

00:43:08.210 --> 00:43:10.110
the atmospheric composition.

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:13.910
So this is, in a way, the
undiscovered and thinking

00:43:13.910 --> 00:43:17.180
outside of your box or at
least find other people

00:43:17.180 --> 00:43:21.020
who have different boxes and
put all of that information

00:43:21.020 --> 00:43:22.680
together.

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:26.060
And of course, the star also
has a huge influence on it.

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:29.210
Whether or not that life
gets hit by red light

00:43:29.210 --> 00:43:32.804
or by white light is a different
influence in its evolution.

00:43:32.804 --> 00:43:34.220
And we don't know
much about this,

00:43:34.220 --> 00:43:37.070
because we only have
our own Earth that

00:43:37.070 --> 00:43:38.960
was hit by white light.

00:43:38.960 --> 00:43:42.080
But these small stars,
as Laura was saying,

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:44.310
are also incredibly active.

00:43:44.310 --> 00:43:48.530
So what would life have to
do to survive like huge UV

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:50.030
on the surface?

00:43:50.030 --> 00:43:52.760
And Laura was talking
about life on the surface,

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:54.770
because of course
life can [? shelter ?]

00:43:54.770 --> 00:43:57.050
on the water or can
[? shelter ?] on the ground.

00:43:57.050 --> 00:43:58.520
And then it doesn't
matter how much

00:43:58.520 --> 00:44:01.080
UV radiation hits the surface.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:03.590
However, we were trying
again to think out

00:44:03.590 --> 00:44:08.060
of the box in our research and
were saying, what does life do?

00:44:08.060 --> 00:44:09.830
What are the different
strategies of life

00:44:09.830 --> 00:44:12.260
if you hit it with a lot of UV?

00:44:12.260 --> 00:44:14.780
And these are algae
that you see here

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:19.190
that when you hit it, actually
it starts to biofluoresce,

00:44:19.190 --> 00:44:22.400
because it lives in
symbiosis with algae.

00:44:22.400 --> 00:44:24.110
The corals start
to biofluoresce,

00:44:24.110 --> 00:44:26.420
because they live in
symbiosis with algaes

00:44:26.420 --> 00:44:29.350
that can survive UV radiation.

00:44:29.350 --> 00:44:32.030
And so it's not to
say at all that that

00:44:32.030 --> 00:44:34.190
would happen on another planet.

00:44:34.190 --> 00:44:37.370
But it is a strategy
that life on a very high

00:44:37.370 --> 00:44:42.170
irradiated environment could
take to actually mitigate

00:44:42.170 --> 00:44:44.660
this harsh UV environment.

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:49.116
And actually biofluorescence
on the earth, we use it.

00:44:49.116 --> 00:44:50.990
We don't use the corals,
because there's only

00:44:50.990 --> 00:44:56.270
0.2% of all the surface of
the life of the earth that

00:44:56.270 --> 00:44:57.830
has corals.

00:44:57.830 --> 00:45:00.710
But this is how we actually
judge whether or not

00:45:00.710 --> 00:45:02.130
plants are healthy.

00:45:02.130 --> 00:45:05.750
We use fluorescence, because
plants also fluoresce.

00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:08.750
Most of the things on the
earth actually fluoresce.

00:45:08.750 --> 00:45:11.000
And if you go to
[INAUDIBLE] aquarium,

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:13.430
it's a little hard
to see, up here

00:45:13.430 --> 00:45:16.010
you see this
biofluorescence corals.

00:45:16.010 --> 00:45:19.130
So most of the aquarium,
if they have UV light,

00:45:19.130 --> 00:45:21.800
these biofluorescent
corals are the ones

00:45:21.800 --> 00:45:26.420
that if they were to make up
these other kind of worlds,

00:45:26.420 --> 00:45:29.900
if that was an evolutionary
path that could work,

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:31.370
a really interesting
idea would be

00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:34.760
you'd have this huge
flare on the star

00:45:34.760 --> 00:45:37.520
and the planet next
to it would light up,

00:45:37.520 --> 00:45:40.760
because it breaks down
the harsh UV radiation

00:45:40.760 --> 00:45:44.130
and gives you additional
visible light.

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:48.610
So the way to think about
it, this undiscovered,

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:52.490
is also to think stretch
your imagination,

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:56.600
because we have this incredibly
diversity of worlds out there.

00:45:56.600 --> 00:45:59.690
And using Earth
and all its facets,

00:45:59.690 --> 00:46:04.070
not just anything we think about
every day, as a Rosetta stone,

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:08.780
is our one way to get at least
a little bit close to the answer

00:46:08.780 --> 00:46:11.180
of how we could
find life out there.

