00:57:18.020 --> 00:57:20.280
costs nothing, and it's
a beautiful present, just

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:21.640
a life choice.

00:57:21.640 --> 00:57:22.150
- Thank you.

00:57:22.150 --> 00:57:22.858
- And I'll just--

00:57:22.858 --> 00:57:24.540
I'll add to that really quickly.

00:57:24.540 --> 00:57:28.250
It's not something you
ever really get used to.

00:57:28.250 --> 00:57:30.200
So I really like
something that Ceili

00:57:30.200 --> 00:57:32.750
said this morning or last
night about the first time she

00:57:32.750 --> 00:57:34.010
saw the Andromeda Galaxy.

00:57:34.010 --> 00:57:36.230
And she said she cried
for like 15 minutes.

00:57:36.230 --> 00:57:39.290
That happened to me the
first time I went observing

00:57:39.290 --> 00:57:42.980
and I saw all of the stars
in the night sky in Chile

00:57:42.980 --> 00:57:46.040
in one of the best observing
sites in the world.

00:57:46.040 --> 00:57:49.010
And I had to take a minute
to go outside and just sob,

00:57:49.010 --> 00:57:51.830
because you can--
it makes it so real

00:57:51.830 --> 00:57:54.050
how many stars and
planets there are.

00:57:54.050 --> 00:57:57.980
And so the sheer number
of inhabitable planets

00:57:57.980 --> 00:58:00.609
in the world or in the universe
is something that you never

00:58:00.609 --> 00:58:01.400
really get used to.

00:58:04.060 --> 00:58:06.270
- I'm Alex from
[INAUDIBLE] High School.

00:58:06.270 --> 00:58:10.220
And do you think that
non-carbon-based life

00:58:10.220 --> 00:58:11.510
forms could exist?

00:58:11.510 --> 00:58:13.290
And are you looking for them?

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:15.510
And another question,
do you think

00:58:15.510 --> 00:58:17.600
that a life form
would have to be

00:58:17.600 --> 00:58:21.440
bipedal to achieve
space flight and go

00:58:21.440 --> 00:58:25.980
to other solar system
or another planet?

00:58:25.980 --> 00:58:27.410
- So great question.

00:58:27.410 --> 00:58:29.820
Let me answer that second
one just very fast.

00:58:29.820 --> 00:58:31.940
Nope, because I
think that's more

00:58:31.940 --> 00:58:33.800
to do with sci-fi
movie budgets and they

00:58:33.800 --> 00:58:36.570
had to fit somebody in there
who had two feet and two legs.

00:58:36.570 --> 00:58:38.510
It was cheaper than do CGI.

00:58:38.510 --> 00:58:40.490
But the first question
is a very good one.

00:58:40.490 --> 00:58:44.450
What about life that's
completely different than ours?

00:58:44.450 --> 00:58:46.070
One thing to think
about it this way

00:58:46.070 --> 00:58:50.120
is life as we know it is
incredibly good in using what's

00:58:50.120 --> 00:58:54.770
around to live or to evolve.

00:58:54.770 --> 00:58:57.110
So that's mostly when you
look at the universe, that's

00:58:57.110 --> 00:58:59.690
hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon.

00:58:59.690 --> 00:59:03.020
So for life to actually
not use carbon and water,

00:59:03.020 --> 00:59:04.980
a couple of things
would have to happen.

00:59:04.980 --> 00:59:08.210
So for whatever reason, even
chemical, they are favorable.

00:59:08.210 --> 00:59:11.240
But if you go to a temperature
range like on Titan

00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:13.460
where it's so cold that
water would freeze,

00:59:13.460 --> 00:59:19.830
you need another solvent if life
always has RNA, DNA, molecules,

00:59:19.830 --> 00:59:21.020
vasculars.

00:59:21.020 --> 00:59:23.150
The problem is I don't
know what to look for.

00:59:23.150 --> 00:59:27.250
So we're designing our missions
for life as we know it.

00:59:27.250 --> 00:59:29.750
We know it involved
the case of one.

00:59:29.750 --> 00:59:32.880
If we ever find life on Titan,
we'll do it for a case of two.

00:59:32.880 --> 00:59:35.540
But right now, case
of one, and then

00:59:35.540 --> 00:59:38.790
we keep our eyes open for
anything weird, because that's

00:59:38.790 --> 00:59:40.850
going to be probably
where even the more

00:59:40.850 --> 00:59:43.280
interesting discoveries are
going to come from, things

00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:44.210
we can't explain.

00:59:44.210 --> 00:59:48.528
And then we'll start a whole
new sort of new research area.

00:59:48.528 --> 00:59:49.028
- Thank you.

00:59:52.940 --> 00:59:55.550
- I'm David Allen.

00:59:55.550 --> 00:59:57.950
This is the third
session in which we've

00:59:57.950 --> 01:00:03.470
heard how social taboos in
the particular discipline

01:00:03.470 --> 01:00:06.800
have prevented data
from coming forward,

01:00:06.800 --> 01:00:10.500
important data that then
eventually lead to taboos--

01:00:10.500 --> 01:00:15.035
excuse me-- led to
really breakthroughs.

01:00:15.035 --> 01:00:18.140
This may not be an
existential crisis.

01:00:18.140 --> 01:00:22.100
And we see this kind of
herd-following behavior

01:00:22.100 --> 01:00:25.570
very much outside of
scientific disciplines.

01:00:25.570 --> 01:00:29.060
But today is about
the undiscovered.

01:00:29.060 --> 01:00:33.350
And it's been operationalized
as celebrating failure

01:00:33.350 --> 01:00:35.790
and the benefits of failure.

01:00:35.790 --> 01:00:39.440
In fact, this
problem of taboos was

01:00:39.440 --> 01:00:41.990
addressed in the first
session in talking

01:00:41.990 --> 01:00:45.370
about how do you grant tenure
to somebody who's failed.

01:00:48.980 --> 01:00:55.310
Let's imagine that this is a
problem of the social climate

01:00:55.310 --> 01:00:58.850
in a discipline and,
as I said also, outside

01:00:58.850 --> 01:01:00.350
of scientific disciplines.

01:01:00.350 --> 01:01:03.800
But that's what we're
talking about today.

01:01:03.800 --> 01:01:07.820
If you'd reflect
in your own domain,

01:01:07.820 --> 01:01:10.940
and if you please beyond
that and other sciences

01:01:10.940 --> 01:01:15.770
or even otherwise,
how might we address

01:01:15.770 --> 01:01:18.260
this what appears to
be a problem if we're

01:01:18.260 --> 01:01:25.100
going to be serious about not
keeping important data hidden?

01:01:25.100 --> 01:01:27.080
- I think one of the
first things I would say

01:01:27.080 --> 01:01:30.950
is science is not
never, ever disconnected

01:01:30.950 --> 01:01:32.090
from the human endeavor.

01:01:32.090 --> 01:01:33.770
We're all humans first.

01:01:33.770 --> 01:01:35.280
And then we train as scientists.

01:01:35.280 --> 01:01:37.571
So there will always be this
thing where, like, oh this

01:01:37.571 --> 01:01:38.180
can't happen.

01:01:38.180 --> 01:01:41.580
But then with enough
evidence, we change our ideas.

01:01:41.580 --> 01:01:43.654
We say, OK, because
other than that,

01:01:43.654 --> 01:01:45.320
we would have never
done this discovery.

01:01:45.320 --> 01:01:47.720
Everybody would have
pushed it under the rug.

01:01:47.720 --> 01:01:50.150
There's enough mounting
evidence to say OK.

01:01:50.150 --> 01:01:55.370
So my human intuition that this
cannot happen is now overrun

01:01:55.370 --> 01:01:59.660
by my analytical training that
I have to look at the facts.

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:01.580
But science is a human endeavor.

01:02:01.580 --> 01:02:04.461
And it takes time for that
to come through, I think.

01:02:04.461 --> 01:02:05.960
- Yeah, I'll just
add to that that I

01:02:05.960 --> 01:02:08.450
think this is a really serious
question that you've raised.

01:02:08.450 --> 01:02:10.550
And in my mind, the
best way to address it

01:02:10.550 --> 01:02:14.540
is by educating kids.

01:02:14.540 --> 01:02:18.350
I wish that every funding
agency had the attitude that you

01:02:18.350 --> 01:02:20.580
have about risk taking.

01:02:20.580 --> 01:02:24.650
But the reality is that we're
accountable to our taxpayers

01:02:24.650 --> 01:02:26.910
who often have--

01:02:26.910 --> 01:02:29.600
who are taught a
mindset about science

01:02:29.600 --> 01:02:31.840
that you have to have your
hypothesis and test it.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:35.210
And so being uncertain
and doing risky things

01:02:35.210 --> 01:02:37.910
and trying to
explore the unknown

01:02:37.910 --> 01:02:40.570
is something that we're not very
comfortable with as a society,

01:02:40.570 --> 01:02:41.410
I would say.

01:02:41.410 --> 01:02:43.310
And so changing
the way science is

01:02:43.310 --> 01:02:46.549
taught so that the next
generation of voters

01:02:46.549 --> 01:02:48.340
and taxpayers is more
comfortable with this

01:02:48.340 --> 01:02:50.360
is, I think, what we should do.

01:02:50.360 --> 01:02:52.880
Looking at you,
high school kids.

01:02:52.880 --> 01:02:55.540
- So human beings are our
real topic [? thing. ?]

01:02:55.540 --> 01:02:56.040
- Yep.

